{\plain \fs24 \b INFERNO CANTO 18}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 1-18.}{\plain \fs24   The extended introductory passage interrupts the narrative in order to set the new \softline
scene: Malebolge, the eighth Circle, with its ten varieties of fraudulent behaviors.  Only in }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  \softline
does an equal number of cantos (17 and 17) create a precise center for a }{\plain \fs24 \i cantica}{\plain \fs24  in the space \softline
between two cantos, and we have just passed it.  The last canto ended with a sort of 'comic' \softline
conclusion to Dante's dangerous voyage on Geryon.  He has now traversed precisely half of the \softline
literary space devoted to the underworld.  Thus, fully half of the }{\plain \fs24 \i cantica}{\plain \fs24 , cantos XVIII to \softline
XXXIV, is dedicated to the sins of Fraud.  That division tells us something about the poet's view \softline
of human behavior, namely that it is better typified by the worst of sins than by the lesser ones.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Robert Durling has developed the schematic idea that all of hell is depicted as having a \softline
structure parallel to that of the human body, with Malebolge representing the belly.  See his \softline
"Deceit and Digestion in the Belly of Hell," in }{\plain \fs24 \i Allegory and Representation: Selected Papers \softline
from the English Institute, 1979-80}{\plain \fs24 , ed. Stephen A. Greenblatt (Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins \softline
University Press, 1981), pp. 61-93; and see the commentary of Durling and Martinez (New York \softline
and Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1996), pp. 552-55; 576-77.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab The poetry of Malebolge, studied by Edoardo Sanguineti }{\plain \fs24 \i (Interpretazione di Malebolge}{\plain \fs24  \softline
[Florence: Olschki, 1962]), is strikingly self-confident.  One has the feeling that Dante, having \softline
finished his apprenticeship, now has achieved a level of aesthetic performance that may have \softline
surprised even him.  In the seventh canto he had conjoined two kinds of sinners, the avaricious \softline
and the prodigal; but these are two sides of the same sin.  Here for the first time, as something of \softline
a }{\plain \fs24 \i tour de force}{\plain \fs24 , he includes two entirely separate categories of sin in a single canto, one of them \softline
itself subdivided into two groups, as in Canto VII -- all of this in 115 lines.  The precision of the \softline
operation is noteworthy, and may be represented as follows:\par
